reviews.reviewText:
Needed a new electric kettle as my previous one died and the Cuisinart CPK-17 seemed to be the best rated across different sites. After a week of use, here are my initial thoughts:

PROS:
The base has a slim profile and takes up little space on the counter;
The electrical cord length can be adjusted under the base to avoid extra slack;
The water level markers are convenient if you want to fill water to a specific amount without the need to boil more water than necessary, which takes longer;
Water boils fairly quickly and accurately based on the taste of my French pressed coffee.

CONS:
The body of the kettle and lid are not insulated so this gets very hot to touch, which is a big letdown compared to some competitors;
Although I was aware there is no digital readout of the water temperature, I found myself missing it when checking the heating progress or even the current water temperature after filling or sitting for a period of time;
Wish the opening was bigger to fit my hand inside to hand dry;
I'm not a huge fan of the rubber push buttons but that may not matter to some people. Although they work completely fine right now, my experience has shown that these types of buttons require more force over time and that the printing will wear out.

I won't list it as a con since it's my fault, but the kettle did fall off my counter after I propped it up to dry up-side-down and the spout dented in while gouging our hardwood floor. It still works just as advertised and the rest of the kettle seems to have a decent build quality.
